There's a whole lot about
you I did not know.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:34.820
Are neural networks-- like
are those passe now?

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:34.990
WOLFF DOBSON: No, no.

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:37.736
People still do neural
networks.

00:04:37.736 --> 00:04:41.480
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Wasn't the cat
detector a neural network?

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:43.590
WOLFF DOBSON: No, neural
networks are still very

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:44.190
interesting.

00:04:44.190 --> 00:04:44.990
There's lots of--

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:47.870
I mean, I had sort of good
old-fashioned AI kind of

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:49.600
stuff, where we are
doing symbolic

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:50.790
representations of things.

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:52.730
But there is also--

00:04:52.730 --> 00:04:53.920
machine learning
is really big.

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:58.520
Machine learning in games is
very interesting because

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.240
machine learning is about
optimization.

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:02.860
A lot of times, it doesn't
actually sell very well when

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:03.980
you're doing it in a game.

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:07.190
So if you're playing a football
game and you're doing

00:05:07.190 --> 00:05:10.180
machine learning on what kind
of plays the guy is doing or

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:14.770
something like that, it will
gradually start getting better

00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:18.220
than you or being able to
predict every move you're

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:18.770
going to make.

00:05:18.770 --> 00:05:21.800
And that's not actually
that much fun.

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:23.170
TODD KERPELMAN: It's not fun
to continually lose?

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:23.850
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, you--

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:24.430
COLT MCANLIS: Ask
the programmer.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:25.360
It's super fun.

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:27.140
WOLFF DOBSON: You don't see
it, and you don't--

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:29.600
if you're doing this gradual
optimization process, you

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:32.530
don't have any place where you
can call attention to and say,

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.510
this is the moment in which
I learned something, and

00:05:34.510 --> 00:05:36.090
therefore, I will
tell you this.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:38.160
Which is why machine
learning--

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:41.260
so if you have a machine
learning thing, a neural

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:44.350
network that's driving your
car, you can't really tell

00:05:44.350 --> 00:05:47.360
it's being driven by a neural
network unless you annotate it

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:49.290
with a whole bunch of stuff,
like, oh, he's missed the

00:05:49.290 --> 00:05:50.670
curve, or something like this.

00:05:50.670 --> 00:05:53.270
So machine learning is
really interesting.

00:05:53.270 --> 00:05:54.760
It's really interesting
in games.

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:59.570
But again, it tends to show up
in quiet ways that you can't

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:00.820
quite see it.

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:03.930
You have showy stuff instead,
to like, look at this AI.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:04.870
It's being so smart.

00:06:04.870 --> 00:06:07.020
That tends to be more of
good old-fashioned AI.

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:08.320
COLT MCANLIS: What do you feel
about modern games today?

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:12.710
Do you think that too much of
the AI isn't really AI?

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:15.543
Because I know a lot of it is
pretty much just pre-canned.

00:06:15.543 --> 00:06:19.670
WOLFF DOBSON: Oh, there's a
whole discussion of what--

00:06:19.670 --> 00:06:22.810
every time something gets
popular, a lot of times, the

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:24.270
AI establishment says,
well, that was never

00:06:24.270 --> 00:06:25.280
really AI all along.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:27.170
That was an optimization
problem or

00:06:27.170 --> 00:06:29.806
something like this.

00:06:29.806 --> 00:06:31.950
For a long time, it was
believable agents.

00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:36.070
You know, how could you make
sidekicks who were believable,

00:06:36.070 --> 00:06:37.590
who seemed like they were
alive and things?

00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:39.880
And then at some point, we
started making games then had

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:41.780
believable agents, dogs
that acted like

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:42.840
dogs, things like that.

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:44.090
There's interesting research--

00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:51.495
No, but like CatZ, C-A-T-Z, the
little pet cats that you

00:06:51.495 --> 00:06:53.000
could have from Broderbund.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.880
I mean, those were moments,
like, believable agents.

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:57.655
Yeah, we can do that.

00:06:57.655 --> 00:06:58.850
Eh, that's not really AI.

00:06:58.850 --> 00:07:02.540
And it goes all the way back to
computer games learning, AI

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:04.330
learning how to play chess.

00:07:04.330 --> 00:07:05.820
At some point, oh,
that's not chess.

00:07:05.820 --> 00:07:07.500
That's just a search problem.

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.120
Or that's not AI,
that's search.

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:10.510
COLT MCANLIS: Well, that's
the goal, right?

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:12.430
I mean, chemistry is really
just physics,

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:13.480
which is really just--

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:14.660
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, exactly.

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:17.230
Well, what I would say about
games not really having real

00:07:17.230 --> 00:07:20.370
AI, what I would actually say
about that is that you only

00:07:20.370 --> 00:07:23.880
need to add as much AI to your
game to make it fun.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:26.960
So there are situations like
if you play Yakuza or

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:30.500
something like that, the AI for
the guys getting out of

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:32.810
your way as you're running
through the crowd is sort of

00:07:32.810 --> 00:07:33.590
silly looking.

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:36.110
They sort of stagger and they
pop to these weird animations,

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:36.970
and all this other stuff.

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:38.190
But you know what?

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:38.890
It's good enough.

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:39.780
I can get through the crowd.

00:07:39.780 --> 00:07:40.660
They get of my way.

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:44.350
And so I think a lot of people,
especially when I was

00:07:44.350 --> 00:07:47.010
in grad school, I would play
these games and think, oh my

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:50.180
gosh, if they just used our
awesome super-advanced

00:07:50.180 --> 00:07:51.440
algorithms, it wouldn't
do this.

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:53.550
And then when you think about
it, it's like, it's not really

00:07:53.550 --> 00:07:56.780
worth the money to get it
that beautiful or to

00:07:56.780 --> 00:07:58.080
make it that seamless.

00:07:58.080 --> 00:07:59.980
And if it isn't perfect and
seamless, you don't even

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:02.210
notice how good it is.

00:08:02.210 --> 00:08:03.520
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Not just
the money, but also the

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:04.950
computation, right?

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:07.340
Like, how much computational
effort is it worth--

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:08.060
TODD KERPELMAN: How much
can you spend towards--

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.350
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yeah, towards
crowd algorithms when you

00:08:11.350 --> 00:08:12.640
don't really notice.

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:13.900
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, exactly.

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:15.305
I mean, if it's happening--

00:08:15.305 --> 00:08:17.510
or a classic example
of this is playing

00:08:17.510 --> 00:08:18.950
first-person shooters.

00:08:18.950 --> 00:08:21.910
If your sidekicks are not--

00:08:21.910 --> 00:08:23.540
if you're playing a single
player game and your sidekicks

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:26.310
are not visible, they could
be doing anything.

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:27.700
And in fact, they usually are.

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:28.820
They're teleporting around.

00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:29.980
They're doing crazy stuff.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:32.289
Because it does not matter what
they're doing, because

00:08:32.289 --> 00:08:33.496
you can't see them.

00:08:33.496 --> 00:08:34.289
TODD KERPELMAN: I have noticed

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:36.664
occasionally if some follower--

00:08:36.664 --> 00:08:39.110
